<script>
  var pathname
  if (window.asset && window.asset.url) {
    // hybrid
    pathname = window.asset.url;
  } else {
    // vi
    pathname = window.location.pathname;
  }

  // remove section label from menu if on corona virus section front
  if (document.querySelector('#masthead-section-label') && window.location.pathname.endsWith("news-event/coronavirus")) {
    var css = '#masthead-section-label { display: none; } ';
    var parent = document.querySelector("#nytslm");
    style = document.createElement('style');
    parent.appendChild(style);

    style.type = 'text/css';
    if (style.styleSheet) {
      // This is required for IE8 and below.
      style.styleSheet.cssText = css;
    } else {
      style.appendChild(document.createTextNode(css));
    }
  }

  var tags = document.getElementsByClassName('nytslm_li_link');

  for (var index = 0; index < tags.length; index++) {
    var el = tags[index];
    if (pathname.length && el && el.href && el.href.includes(pathname)) {
      el.classList.add("nytsMenu_li_current");
      break;
    }
  }

  function removeLiveBug() {
    var found = false;
    var spans = document.querySelectorAll('span');
    for (var index = 0; index < spans.length; index++) {
      if (spans[index].textContent === 'LIVE UPDATES') {
        found = true;
        break;
      }
    }

    if (found) {
      var live = document.querySelector('#live');
      if (live) live.remove();
    }
  }

  removeLiveBug();
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', removeLiveBug);

</script>

Times</span></span></figcaption></figure></div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The coronavirus pandemic has now killed more than 200,000 people and sickened more than 2.8 million worldwide, <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/coronavirus-maps.html" title="">according to data collected by The New York Times</a>. At least 177 countries have reported cases of Covid-19, the disease caused by the virus.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The actual toll is higher by an unknown degree, and will remain so for some time. A Times review of mortality data in 12 countries showed that <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/04/21/world/coronavirus-missing-deaths.html" title="">official tallies have undercounted deaths</a> during the outbreak, largely because of limited testing. Several thousand people in New York City who died without testing positive for Covid-19, and thousands more in other countries, are considered probable cases.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Still, the official numbers offer a sense of the scale and speed of the pandemic. The pace of the virus’s spread can be measured in doubling, and the known global death count <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/10/world/coronavirus-world-news-updates.html#link-3c51d1b9" title="">surpassed 100,000</a> on April 10, just more than two weeks ago.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0"><a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/us/coronavirus-us-cases.html" title="">The United States has by far the world’s largest known outbreak</a>, with more than 950,000 cases and a death toll approaching 50,000. Europe has also been hard-hit. There are more than 26,000 deaths among the 197,000 known cases <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/europe/italy-coronavirus-cases.html" title="">in Italy</a>, and more than 23,000 deaths among the 207,000 in Spain.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Only two other countries have confirmed more than 20,000 deaths: <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/europe/france-coronavirus-cases.html" title="">France</a>, with more than 22,800; and <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/europe/united-kingdom-coronavirus-cases.html" title="">Britain</a>, which crossed into that range on Saturday. <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/europe/germany-coronavirus-cases.html" title="">Germany</a> and Turkey both have outbreaks of more than 100,000 cases, but their official death tolls are lower.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Deaths per capita offers another measure of the pandemic. Belgium, with about 12 million people, has suffered the second highest such toll, according to the Times database, with 62 deaths per 100,000 people. But Belgium’s toll may reflect its <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/04/21/world/coronavirus-missing-deaths.html" title="">more complete counting of deaths</a>. Unlike many other countries, Belgium includes in its count deaths at nursing homes, where clustered, elderly populations are especially vulnerable. Spain’s reported toll is 50 deaths per 100,000 people, and Italy’s is 44. The United States’s is 15 per 100,000 people.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Most countries do not report deaths that occur outside of hospitals. Deaths that occurred before the virus was known to be circulating — <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/22/us/santa-clara-county-coronavirus-death.html" title="">like two in Santa Clara County, Calif., in February</a> — are only starting to be re-examined. Further, some countries may be deliberately undercounting their tolls.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-11b00688">Italy’s prime minister details how the country will begin to ease Europe’s longest lockdown.</h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">After enduring the longest lockdown in Europe and one of the world’s most deadly coronavirus outbreaks, Italians heard the details on Sunday of Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte’s plan to ease restrictions and reopen their economy starting on May 4. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">“Now begins the phase, for everybody, of living with the virus,” Mr. Conte said in a prime-time address on Sunday night, adding that a failure to respect social distancing would cause infections to climb again and the government to “close the tap.”</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0"> “If you love Italy,” he implored, “maintain distance.”</p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The government has had to constantly weigh Italy’s economic interests, and those of millions of struggling Italians, with the public health of the entire country. It has been an excruciating balance, but Mr. Conte’s government has decided that the country, which entered a lockdown on March 10, could not stay closed indefinitely.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">While gatherings and parties remain banned, and travel remains closely regulated, with special auto-certification forms required for movement, Mr. Conte said that the visiting of relatives will be allowed to people within Italian regions on May 4.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">“There always has to be a reason to move around,” he said.</p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Schools, he said, would remain closed for the rest of the academic year, as his scientific advisers had informed him that the return of students could trigger an explosion of cases.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">He added that the danger was intensified by the high average age of Italy’s teachers.</p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Mr. Conte fixed a price for individual masks at 50 cents to prevent price gouging and said that the manufacturing and construction sectors would be allowed to operate as long as workers observed social distancing and wore masks.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The official count of virus-related deaths in Italy stands at 26,644,<span class="css-8l6xbc evw5hdy0">  </span>but experts say the real number is far higher. Mr. Conte said that funerals would once again be permitted beginning on May 4, but they would be limited to 15 people, preferably in an outdoor setting. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Parks may also reopen on that date, subject to the approval of local mayors and regional governors, and outdoor exercise, such as jogging, could be carried out more than 200 meters from home.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Restaurants could begin offering takeout, not just delivery.</p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Mr. Conte also gave a preview of businesses that could reopen down the road. On May 18, he said, stores could possibly open. Coffee bars, restaurants, hairdressers and beauticians would open no sooner than June 1.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Asked by a reporter when free movement could return, he said that a potential phase three would arrive with the discovery of a vaccine. Until then, he said, “We must get ready for phase 2.” </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-46b7fc4d">The virus poses a dire threat in overcrowded prisons, leading governments around the world to release inmates. </h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Prisons have become powerful breeding grounds for the coronavirus, prompting governments to release hundreds of thousands of inmates in a scramble to curb the spread of the contagion behind bars.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The pandemic has also set off rebellions as angry inmates have called new attention to chronic problems in corrections systems in many countries, including filth, limited access to health care and overcrowding.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">As the virus plunged virtually every country into crisis mode,<a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/OPCAT/AdviceStatePartiesCoronavirusPandemic2020.pdf" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"> United Nations experts on detention, </a>the <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="http://www.euro.who.int/__data/assets/pdf_file/0019/434026/Preparedness-prevention-and-control-of-COVID-19-in-prisons.pdf" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">World Health Organization</a> and human <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/04/14/covid-19-human-rights-checklist" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">rights activists</a> have urged governments to reduce their prisoner populations swiftly.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">“In many countries, detention facilities are overcrowded, in some cases dangerously so,” Michelle Bachelet, the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights, <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://news.un.org/en/story/2020/03/1060252" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">said in a statement.</a> “The consequences of neglecting them are potentially catastrophic.”</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">At least 125 countries hold more prisoners than their correctional systems were designed for, including 20 that have more than two times the number of inmates they’re equipped to secure, according to <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.prisonstudies.org/highest-to-lowest/occupancy-level?field_region_taxonomy_tid=All" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">the database World Prison Brief</a>.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Brazil has one of the largest and most overloaded prison systems. Andrelina Amelia Ferreira, who heads the Mothers of Jail Movement in São Paulo, said she had received hundreds of messages from women whose loved ones are locked up. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">“I’m scared I will die in prison,” one man wrote to his wife, describing a high fever and a lack of food. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">In New York, as of Tuesday, the coronavirus had killed six inmates and sickened hundreds. The actor Alec Baldwin on Sunday <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://twitter.com/ScottHech/status/1254385747492253696" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">called on Governor Cuomo</a> to release vulnerable inmates from New York State prisons, including older inmates, pregnant women and those who were immunocompromised.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-2694208a">Cuba is sending doctors to South Africa and around the world to fight the pandemic.</h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Cuba, a country known for dispatching doctors to needy countries as part of a decades-long medical diplomacy effort, <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://twitter.com/EmbassyCubaZA/status/1254167294739087360" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">said on Saturday</a> it was sending more than 200 doctors and other specialists to South Africa.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The contingent is part of more than 1,200 Cuban health professionals deployed to 22 countries to help fight the pandemic. The group was scheduled to arrive at an airport near Johannesburg on Sunday, according to the Cuban Embassy in South Africa.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Since the 1960s, Cuba has sent more than 100,000 workers to countries that have requested help. More than 30,000 Cuban doctors, nurses, technicians are currently deployed in more than 60 countries, mostly in Latin America, Asia and Africa. Cuban doctors have helped fight the Ebola virus in West Africa, blindness in Latin America and cholera in Haiti. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div id="NYT_MID_MAIN_CONTENT_REGION" class="css-9tf9ac"><section id="styln-covid-updates-world" class="css-l08pwh interactive-content interactive-size-medium"><div class="css-17ih8de interactive-body"><!--

</div></section></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The efforts<a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/08/world/americas/in-haitis-cholera-fight-cuba-takes-lead-role.html" title=""> have earned the country praise for bringing medical help</a> to the front lines of a crisis. </p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">But they have also drawn criticism, including from those who suggest the deployments are a way of deflecting attention from the government’s <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2020/country-chapters/cuba" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">poor human rights record</a>. The programs <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2020/feb/11/trump-puts-cuban-doctors-in-firing-line-as-heat-turned-up-on-island-economy" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">have also been seen</a> as a tool to exert Cuban influence around the world.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">In most cases, Cuba has charged other countries for the services. Some <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/29/world/americas/brazil-cuban-doctors-revolt.html" title="">doctors have criticized the arrangement, </a>saying they get too small a share of the money, and moved to break ranks with the government. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">But Cuba has never charged for disaster response or medical emergency deployments before the pandemic, Cuban officials said. It’s not clear if Cuba is charging for the coronavirus deployments. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">After the coronavirus pandemic hit, Cuba dispatched its doctors and other health professionals to Belize, Nicaragua, Angola and Qatar, among other countries. On March 23, Cuban doctors were deployed to Italy to fight the outbreak there, the first time its doctors have been sent to Europe.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The group in South Africa includes family physicians, epidemiologists, biotechnology experts and other specialists, according to the Cuban Embassy in South Africa.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1sngw6j"><a class="css-1a9ghz5" href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/world/coronavirus-maps.html"><div class="css-1eoytci"><img alt="" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2020/03/03/world/coronavirus-map-promo/coronavirus-map-promo-articleLarge-v335.png"/></div><div class="css-1rha1bf"><h2 class="css-zd32qr">Coronavirus Map: Tracking the Global Outbreak</h2><p class="css-1uuihdo">The virus has infected more than 2,918,000 people in at least 177 countries.</p></div></a></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-b7ec96c">Prime Minister Boris Johnson has returned to Downing Street and will be at work on Monday.</h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Weeks after entering the hospital for the coronavirus and being treated in an intensive care unit, Prime Minister Boris Johnson of Britain returned to 10 Downing Street on Sunday, and heads back to work on Monday to resume leading the government’s response to the pandemic.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Mr. Johnson is “raring to go,” a Downing Street spokeswoman said by telephone on Sunday.<span class="css-8l6xbc evw5hdy0">  </span></p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">While battling the virus, the prime minister had deputized Foreign Secretary Dominic Raab to carry out certain duties. Mr. Johnson had revealed on March 27 that he was infected, but continued to work. When his condition worsened, he was admitted to St. Thomas’ Hospital in London on April 5. The next day, <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/world/europe/boris-johnson-coronavirus-hospital-intensive-care.html?action=click&amp;module=RelatedLinks&amp;pgtype=Article" title="">the prime minister was moved into intensive care</a> after his condition deteriorated, and he was given oxygen treatment. The government said Mr. Johnson did not require a ventilator.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0"><a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/world/europe/boris-johnson-coronavirus.html?searchResultPosition=4" title="">He was discharged on April 12 </a>and had been recuperating at Chequers, the prime minister’s country house. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">In his absence, each evening a rotating roster of cabinet ministers and two expert advisers have given the nation a coronavirus update from Downing Street. The briefings are the antithesis of the fiery, freewheeling spectacle presided over by President Trump. There is none of the gladiatorial combat of Mr. Trump’s clashes with reporters, none of the awkward moments when the leader second-guesses the scientists and no fulsome expressions of praise by subordinates.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Yet despite the cultural differences, there are deeper parallels between the sessions. And now, Mr. Johnson faces what one cabinet member called “the political calculus of life and death”: how to ease the lockdown. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The question becomes more urgent as springtime temperatures rise and more people in Britain leave their homes. Already, officials said at a news briefing on Saturday, the number of passengers using London’s subway had risen after falling drastically during the lockdown.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">On Sunday, Mr. Raab told Sky News that the government should act cautiously to avoid a second spike in infections and a second lockdown that would damage public confidence.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">“We are at a delicate and dangerous stage, and we need to make sure that the next steps are sure-footed,” he said, adding that the government was “doing the homework” on what would happen in the next phase.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Britain had more than 152,000 confirmed cases as of Sunday, and more than 20,000 deaths.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-51820924">Children in Spain go outside for the first time in weeks as the country’s lockdown begins to ease.</h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><figure class="sizeLarge css-qhlm6o" aria-label="media" role="group"><div class="css-bsn42l"><span class="css-1dv1kvn">Video</span><div><div class="css-1t0v8sy etkm6pg0"><div class="css-mm3pwi"><script class="css-cch8ym"><span class="css-1dv1kvn">Credit</span><span itemProp="copyrightHolder" class="emkp2hg2 css-1fxp258 e1z0qqy90"><span class="css-1ly73wi e1tej78p0">Credit...</span><span>Samuel Aranda for The New York Times</span></span></span></figcaption></figure><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Children took to the streets of Spain on Sunday for the first time in six weeks, as part of the government’s plan to gradually ease a nationwide lockdown in response to improved coronavirus numbers.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The rules allow children to take a stroll for one hour within one kilometer (0.6 miles) of their home, accompanied by an adult. And the sight of parents pushing strollers and teenagers riding skateboards brought a semblance of normalcy to Madrid and elsewhere.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Paulino Motter, a Brazilian resident of Madrid, said he and his 7-year-old daughter, Helena, had decided to take their usual morning walk to school, even though it was a Sunday. “I felt it was important to show her that the city has changed, but that her life can hopefully return to normal at some point,” Mr. Motter said.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Beatriz Teja was helping her 2-year-old son, Juan, steer his miniature blue racing bike down Calle Serrano, one of Madrid’s main shopping avenues. “I cannot believe that it is over 40 days since Juan has been out,” she said. “We hear all the time about health, but I really think that keeping a child at home for so long cannot in any way have been good for his health.”</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Prime Minister Pedro Sánchez said on Saturday that adults would also be allowed outdoors to take a stroll or exercise from May 2 if the improvement in Spain’s coronavirus figures continues.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">On Sunday, the country reported 288 deaths overnight — the first time that the daily number of fatalities had fallen below 300 since March 18, shortly after the lockdown came into force.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-1770b7b2">Two Dutch mink farms are quarantined after the animals are infected with the virus.</h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Two mink farms in the Netherlands have been quarantined after the animals were found to have the coronavirus, the Dutch Agricultural Ministry said on Sunday.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">It is believed to be the first time that minks were reported to be infected during the pandemic.</p><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The minks’ symptoms included respiratory problems, the ministry <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.rijksoverheid.nl/actueel/nieuws/2020/04/26/covid-19-geconstateerd-op-twee-nertsenbedrijven" title="" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">said in a statement</a>, and they are believed to have contracted the virus from farm employees.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The agriculture minister, Carola Schouten, said that mink farmers, veterinarians and researchers would now be required to report any respiratory problems or increased mortality in minks in the country. The order does not extend to other livestock, since they do not appear to be susceptible to the virus, the statement said.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">Investigations have begun to determine the source of the infections, the statement said, and air and dust samples were taken near the farms to test for traces of the virus. As a precautionary measure the department advised people to avoid cycling or walking within about 1,300 feet of the farms.</p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><p class="css-exrw3m evys1bk0">The coronavirus has also been detected in other animals around the globe since the pandemic began, including <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/22/health/cats-pets-coronavirus.html" title="">two pet cats from different parts of New York State</a>, a <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/science/animals-pets-coronavirus.html" title="">pet dog in Hong Kong</a> and a <a class="css-1g7m0tk" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/06/science/tiger-cats-coronavirus.html" title="">tiger at the Bronx Zoo</a>. </p></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><div class="css-1fanzo5 StoryBodyCompanionColumn"><div class="css-53u6y8"><h2 class="css-1j6xuz eoo0vm40" id="link-33a61248">In North Korea, which has reported no coronavirus cases, rumors fly about the health of Kim Jong-un.</h2></div><aside class="css-ew4tgv" aria-label="companion column"></aside></div><figure class="sizeMedium css-qhlm6o" aria-label="media" role="group"><div class="css-bsn42l"><span class="css-1dv1kvn">Video</span><div><div class="css-1t0v8sy etkm6pg0"><div class="css-mm3pwi"><div class="css-1g7y0i5 e1drnplw0"><button tabindex="100" class="css-1rtlxy" type="button" aria-label="close"><svg width="60" height="60" viewBox="0 0 60 60" fill="none"><circle cx="30" cy="30" r="30" fill="white" fill-opacity="0.9"></circle><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M38.4844 20.1006L39.8986 21.5148L21.5138 39.8996L20.0996 38.4854L38.4844 20.1006Z" fill="black"></path><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M21.5156 20.1006L20.1014
